That can collapse again and again. And it did for me when I was spending time on retreat practicing vipassana. But I always associated it with the intense concentration of retreat. And it seemed unavailable to me in ordinary moments of consciousness.

1151
01:55:37,160 --> 01:55:48,160
You know, off retreat, you know, I'm driving in traffic or, you know, working at my computer or whatever. Like there's no way I'm going to touch that level of concentration. You know, I haven't been spending 14 hours a day meditating.

1152
01:55:48,160 --> 01:56:04,160
So this is a kind of a peak experience that isn't available now. Well, with zouchen you discover that the reverse is true. All the peak experiences are no more empty of self than ordinary waking consciousness is.

1153
01:56:04,160 --> 01:56:15,160
And you can recognize this about consciousness in any moment. And it doesn't actually require previous moments of building momentum.

1154
01:56:15,160 --> 01:56:32,160
Framing really counts for a lot here. So I spent a lot of time practicing with this one Burmese meditation master Upandita Sayedow. And the analogy he would often use is that progress in vipassana is like rubbing two sticks together to get fire.

1155
01:56:32,160 --> 01:56:46,160
The moment you stop, the heat dissipates and you're back to zero. Right? So it's like you'd have the sense of you'd be on retreat with him practicing for, you know, up to 20 hours a day and trying to make your mindfulness absolutely continuous.

1156
01:56:46,160 --> 01:57:01,160
So that's the difference between sitting and walking meditation and every other moment. I mean, you're doing a ton of sitting and walking meditation. It's like 16 hours a day of that. But every other moment when like you're going to meals or anything else, you wake up and get out of bed in the morning.

1157
01:57:01,160 --> 01:57:26,160
Every transitional moment, getting a cup of tea. You're trying to link every instant of conscious awareness together with mindfulness. And whenever you would get distracted, part of you would begin scoring that as a failure to build up enough momentum to get to the goal of the fundamental breakthrough that was on offer by that path.

1158
01:57:26,160 --> 01:57:38,160
So this framing, this idea that you're rubbing two sticks together, the moment you stop, they're cooling off and you've made no progress. Right? That's the opposite framing for zogchen.

1159
01:57:38,160 --> 01:57:54,160
The framing you need for zogchen is there's this something already true of consciousness. You're not trying to produce this thing. You're not trying to get rid of the ego. You're not trying to change anything about what is.

1160
01:57:54,160 --> 01:58:08,160
You're trying to recognize a feature of consciousness that is already the case. And it's actually nearer to you than you think. It's not a matter of going deep within and having some kind of breakthrough.

1161
01:58:08,160 --> 01:58:18,160
It's actually right on the surface of the most ordinary form of consciousness. It doesn't require any pyrotechnic change in the contents of consciousness.

1162
01:58:18,160 --> 01:58:34,160
You're not actually closer to it if you take acid and all the colors begin to change. You feel a change in your energy such that you feel this kind of buzz of connectedness to all things.

1163
01:58:34,160 --> 01:58:46,160
As anyone who's taken acid can verify that's on offer. But all of that's interesting. All of that's, I'm not discounting the power of those experiences.

1164
01:58:47,160 --> 01:59:04,160
Those experiences are no less empty of self than every state of consciousness. It's precisely the state of consciousness that's compatible with reaching for a glass of water and drinking it without anything novel intruding.

1165
01:59:04,160 --> 01:59:18,160
There's no bliss. There's no rapture. There's no profound or spiritual change in state. It's possible to recognize in that moment that there's no center to consciousness.

1166
01:59:18,160 --> 01:59:29,160
What Zogchen is, is the path of discovering that there's no center and then taking that insight as your only object of mindfulness.

1167
01:59:29,160 --> 01:59:36,160
So that what you're mindful of thereafter is that there's no center to consciousness.

1168
01:59:36,160 --> 01:59:45,160
So whatever is appearing, sights, sounds, sensations, you are continually dropping the implied center.

1169
01:59:45,160 --> 02:00:07,160
It's kind of a steep path because it's hard to start. You can't really start. I mean, everything you're doing before you have that insight and can notice it again on demand, everything you're doing is by definition a preliminary practice to that because you need enough mindfulness to notice what is to be noticed and to follow the instructions to start that path.

1170
02:00:07,160 --> 02:00:18,160
But you certainly don't have to have spent years on retreat to start that path. And so having good information is certainly better than having misleading information there.

1171
02:00:18,160 --> 02:00:36,160
